My buddy & researcher Lawrence asked me to jump on video to watch the red-spot night octopus hunt! 

Endemic to tropical Australia, this nocturnal species spends most of its time hiding underground. 

Isn’t she beautiful?!

📸: @brandon_hannan_photography⁣

⚠️ Not to be confused with an Algae Octopus, the Hairy octopus gets it's name from the hundreds of tiny skin spikes they have on their body that resemble hair blowing in the water. 
⁣
👾 They are MUCH smaller than most anticipate, this one is only an inch long! (Full grown they’re smaller than a golf ball!) 
⁣
🤔 Have you ever heard of this species?⁣
⁣
😅 We like to affectionately refer to them as the Chewbactopus LOL⁣
⁣
🗣 Here is what Videographer Brandon had to say... ⁣
⁣
🤩 “To say I am excited is an understatement. This video below is of a Hairy Octopus. To my knowledge I don’t think anyone has found them here in Okinawa, Japan. This is a bucket list cephalopod for me. I spent 35 mins watching and photographing this guy. Truly amazing this guy is only 1in. in size.” ⁣
⁣
Know someone who would think this lil’critter is cute? Tag em below for #OCTOpusMonth! ⁣

🗣 Tag some friends below and spend the weekend drawing octopuses! ⁣
⁣
OctoNation & @briankesinger Kesinger got together a couple weeks ago and put on a how-to class for beginners! Just search OctoNation on YouTube! These are some of the drawings from class! ⁣⁣
⁣
⚠️ Make sure you tag #OctoNation & #BrianKesinger so we can see your work! ⁣
⁣
👨‍🎨 @BrianKesinger is an award winning story artist, illustrator and author. His 20+ year career at Disney has spanned both hand drawn and CG animated films from Tarzan to Frozen 2. In addition to Brian's film work, he has also become a celebrated author and illustrator of several books that showcase his style, wit and ability to tell engaging stories in original ways. His artistic journey has lead him to find an additional home with Marvel Comics and Lucasfilm where he blends his animation background with the comic art form to create dazzling and expressive art! ⁣
⁣
Long Story Short— Brian is a LEGEND! (Also- he’s the youngest person to have been hired to Disney animation studios at the age of 18) ⁣⁣
⁣
If you read this far comment “Lezz draw some octoz!” & tag some buddies ✏️ 🐙⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣

Cirrate octopuses have a small, internal “U” saddle shaped shell to support the two big flappy fins on their head! ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
@NautilusLive captured this footage while diving 1580m deep (.98 miles) along a seamount located southwest of Baker Island (almost halfway between Hawaii and Australia)⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
🥇 This species has the deepest known living cephalopod record — being spotted at 7,000m deep (4.35 miles deep!) ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⚠️ It’s name? Cirroteuthis Muelleri— it’s one of the largest cirrate octopuses, growing to a length of 1.5 metres (4.9 ft)⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🐘: so it’s basically a giant dumbo octopus! 🤩⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
👗 you’ve probably noticed that Cirrate octopuses have quite the dress! Observe how the webbing can extend to the very tips of their arms! ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
🤩 The name Cirrate comes from the long slender  hair-like structures called ‘cirri’ that MIGHT aid these critters in the capture of food. They have only one row of suckers. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
Lining both sides of the suckers you can see long slender muscular papillae (look closely towards the middle of this video!) ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
What do you think of these solar flare looking  beauties Nation? ⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
A profound THANK YOU to #NautilusLIVE team for exploring areas of the ocean that have never been explored before!  Hit the mail icon and share this video to your stories if ya wanna pass this information along! <3 <3 <3 ⁣⁣⁣⁣

🐙🥇The smallest, teeniest, tiniest octopus on the planet! 📸: @brandon_hannan_photography 

Say howdy to the star-sucker pygmy octopus (octopus wolfi) 

Fascinating Facts: 
🔹 Smaller than an inch (25mm) 

🔹 weighs less than a gram (.04oz) a paper clip! 

🔹 Females can lay multiple clutches/festoons of eggs vs. dying after brooding one. 

🔹it’s hard to tell the difference between baby wolfi and full grown adult wolfi because they’re miniature versions of the adults! 😅

🔹They’ve got a lifespan of around 6-18 months

🔹they’ve got little fringes of skin (papillae) on their suckers - probably for better grip strength so they don’t blow away (or to capture prey) 

Anyway —One thing is for sure. 

We’re in LOVE WIT THOS SMOL EYEBOLLZ!!! *squeeeee* 

I feel like if @world_record_egg can go viral — this star-sucker Pygmy octopus can go viral too 😅

If ya read this far -
Share your favorite photo of this QT to your stories! 

Photographer @brandon_hannan_photography  said “This species is rare to see in Okinawa, but mainly because of its size. The ones I found were only the size of my thumb nail making it easy to miss if you don’t know what to look for!”

The glass octopus is having a moment! 🤩 🎥: @schmidtocean 
Have you ever heard of the Glass Octopus?
🦹‍♀️ This octopuses superpower is it’s see through skin! 

🌊 They spend their whole lives floating in the open sea— so having a nearly invisible body comes in super handy 😅

If ya look close, the only things visible are their digestive gland, optic nerves & eyes 👀 

Glass octopuses keep their bodies vertical 🙃 in the water column or “spindle shaped”

Glass octos figured out that if they keep their bodies horizontal their digestive gland casts more of a shadow to predators!

Yeah, no thanks! They’re too smart for all of that🦈 

... The mating process is super unique with this species… 

normally a male octopus breaks the tip of his specialized arm filled with packets of sperm (called the hectocotylus) and swims off... 

Well the male glass octopus’ arm doesn’t break off! 😅 (sounds dangerous if you consider some species of female octopuses will eat the male)

The male will completely envelop the female in his webbing making sure that the sperm is released exactly where it needs to go! (I have a picture of the glass octopuses special arm if you’re interested in seeing it — DM us 😅) 

Ok so then what? 

The female glass octopus broods/matures all the eggs inside of her mantle (body) as she navigates the massive open ocean!

They hatch directly from her and the cycle begins all over again. 

If ya read this far— what did ya find most interesting? 

Also now that #SharkWeek is over - do ya think it’s time for Octopus Week to be a thing (but for 8 days of course) 

✍️ : @octonation

Quiz: Can you name at least 5 species of octopus off the top of your head? Go! 
📸 @andrey_shpatak 

The hairy octopus is one of the smallest octo species on the planet growing a little bigger than 40mm (1.5 inches) 

You won’t see many pictures of this beauty online because, well… they’re super hard to spot! 

As a result of their elusive nature— we’re not sure what they eat, who their predators are, how long they live for, or what their eggs look like! 

They don’t even have an official scientific name 🧐

The only information we have has been collected by underwater photographers in our network who found this adorable Pom-Pom ball looking octopus totally captivating. 

If ya read this far, congrats— you are the less than 1% of people on this planet who know about this undescribed species!

Rate this camouflage from 1 to 8
🎥: @DavidDiez (learn more ⬇️) 
🔺Octopus can form 3D skin bumps to texture match their surroundings— but does it tire them out? Turns out they don’t give it much thought! 

💪🏼 Octopus have a unique specialized musculature that’s similar to when clams squeeze & lock their shells to protect themselves. 

🔐 Rather than exerting energy to keep their clam shell shut, the tension is maintained by smooth muscles that fit like a lock and key until a chemical signal (neurotransmitter) releases them. 

🐙 Scientists believe that octopus skin can “catch” the look of the landscape they are on & hold the shape effortlessly without any neural input for up to an hour. 

Who else is endlessly fascinated by octopuses? Tag a buddy below!

🐙🦀 What’s your favorite novelty ice cream treat? Happy #nationalicecreamday!
⚠️ What merch should we create with this new character? Tanks? Pins? Stickers? 
👋 Meet Crabby Chris, the magnificent Mimic Octopus! 

🦀 Crabby Chris really got his name from his favorite ice cream treat. He would be inclined to tell you it’s the best and if you argue with him… you might end up saying that he’s a crabby character, especially when he mimics his lion-fish pals! Chris is a solitary creature most of the time but when he hears those ice cream submarine songs, he can’t help but come out to snag a treat!   🍦☀️ Crabby Chris is 1 of 4 in our new species specific summer series where our team works to achieve our nonprofits mission of inspiring wonder of the ocean by educating the world about octopuses. Our creative director @chrisacreative knocks it out of the park every time! 

🎉 It’s a super fun way for us to teach about the biodiversity within the octopus species and is guaranteed to help you start conversations about your favorite creature out in the wild! 
😄🐙🥰   ❓ For those of you who have been following along— how can you tell the difference between a Mimic Octopus and a Wunderpus? — can you see the identifying mark here?

You can check out our previous Octo-barista series by visiting the link in our bio! (We just restocked stickers and other items!)   Crabby Chris merch coming soon— you excited? Let us know! Till then— thanks for all your love and let us know your favorite nostalgic ice cream treat!

One of the smallest octopuses on earth! 
📸: @brandon_hannan_photography⁣
The Hairy octopus got its nickname from the hundreds of branched skin spikes that float around like hair. 
🌱 The hair-lookin’ growths help it camouflage as it blends into plants and algae. 
⁣
👾 They are WAYYYY smaller than most anticipate, this one is only 25.4mm long (1 inch) 
⁣
🤔 Have you ever heard of this species before? They still don’t have an official scientific name.   📕 The little we know about the hairy Octopus comes from the reports of divers… we aren’t sure of their lifespan, mating habits, and even their specific diets. 
⁣
😅 We like to affectionately refer to them as the Chewbactopus… what other nicknames can you think of?
⁣
🗣 Here is what Videographer Brandon had to say... ⁣
⁣
🤩 “To say I am excited is an understatement. This video below is of a Hairy Octopus. To my knowledge I don’t think anyone has found them here in Okinawa, Japan. This is a bucket list cephalopod for me. I spent 35 mins watching and photographing this guy. Truly amazing this guy is only 1in. in size.”   ⚠️ If ya read this far, then you know more than most about one of the smallest octopus species on this planet!   ✈️ Share this pom-pom looking beauty in your stories and educate your friends.  📸 If you’d like to see more photos visit our Octopus Encyclopedia (octopedia) at OctoNation.com

⚠️ Roll Call: where in the world do you live?  🎥 @VideoBubbles (Learn More ⬇️)
 Besides the giant pacific octopus, Octopus Cyanea, also known as the day octopus, is one of the largest known species of octopus with its total length greater than 1m (over 3 ft!)

💀They live FAST, and die young. It might be shocking to discover that their lifespan is only 12-15 months max! (Which is typical of warmer water species) 

🐙 This stunning octopus hunts during the day-time searching for mussels, clams, shrimps, and crabs hiding among the corals and crevices. 

👗 They have the ability to canvas a coral with their balloon-like arms while blowing jets to water to eject prey into their suckers  🔎 Are you ready for more help Identifying this species amongst others?  📖 The most distinguishing body pattern features include 3 to 7 rows of small white spots on the arm tips that are distinct against a dark brown body color. The day octopus also has false eye spots (ocelli) present at the base of its arm that are dark oval patches with no iridescent rings! 

Can you see these features in the video? Let us know! 

If ya read this far, visit OctopusFacts.com and join our text community called OCTOPOLIS where we send out octo facts every now and then and merch releases before anyone knows :)

🤩 Wait for it…  🎥: @RomanHurghada 👑 The Bobtail squid is an interesting cephalopod that kinda look like an octopus and a squid … but it turns out they’re more closely related to the cuttlefish!   Unlike cuttlefish though, they don’t have a fin skirt that wraps around their body… or even a cuttlebone to help them float!   👼 Instead, Bobtails gotta flap their little angel wings (paddle-fins) on their cute plump bodies to move around! That’s alotta cardio 😅  If you look closely you can also see this one using jet propulsion to maintain buoyancy with its siphon located under its arms.   At dawn (and to escape predators) they’ll blow jets of water to make a little nook for their bodies and then flail their arms around to cover themselves in sand.   Wondering why the top half of them looks like the sea floor?  They secret a super sticky mucus that helps rocks & sand stick to their backs— funnily enough, scientists call this layer a jello jacket! Haha!  Read this far? Comment “Jello Jacket for the win!” Or… “SQUIDZ IN SPACE” — let us explain…   Bobtail squids were sent into space last month to examine the effects of spaceflight on interactions between beneficial microbes and their animal hosts.   Hmmm…Hopefully they’ll be rescued by their 👽 alien relatives. We’ll wait on the update from @NASA 🤣
